wer. At the same time as American universities were producing good readers by the hundreds, many more thousands of bad readers were learning elsewhere to be disciplined public communicators, whether in diplomatic and ambassadorial missions, private and public cultural exchange programs, multinational corporations, or global activist groups. As we grapple with literature’s diminished role in the public sphere, Paraliterary suggests a new way to think about literature, its audience, and its potential, one that looks at the civic institutions that have long engaged readers ignored by the academy.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 0aBooks and readingzUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aBooks and readingzUnited StatesxSociological aspects. 0aBooks and reading--United States--History--20th century. 0aCommunication in international relationszUnited States. 0aLiterature and societyzUnited States. 0aReadingxPhilosophy. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / General.2bisacsh  acultural diplomacy.  ainstitutional sociology.  aparaliterary.  apostwar literature.  asociology of reading.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2017z978311071193640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226474021423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226474021/original  a978-3-11-071193-6  University of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2017b2017  aGBV-deGruyter-alles